{"cursor":"12738","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox museum |name = National Film and Sound Archive |image = National Film\nand Sound Archive.jpg |type = Audiovisual Archive |established = 1984 |location\n= Acton, Australian Capital Territory, Australia |website = }} The 'National\nFilm and Sound Archive' (NFSA) is Australiaâs audiovisual archive, responsible\nfor developing, preserving, maintaining, promoting and providing access to a\nnational collection of audiovisual materials and related items. The collection\nranges from works created in the late nineteenth century when the recorded sound\nand film industries were in their infancy to those made in the present day.\n\nAs an institution, the Archive had a chequered history from its first\nincarnation in 1935 as the National Historical Film and Speaking Record Library\n(within the then Commonwealth National Library) to its becoming an independent\nstatutory authority as the National Film and Sound Archive of Australia in 2008.\n\nIt is located in Canberra, the nation's capital city.\n","linknr":205,"url":"National_Film_and_Sound_Archive","recorded":1362686007,"links":17,"instances":["australia","film_director","government"],"pdf":["http://www.aph.gov.au/library/pubs/bd/2007-08/08bd077.pdf"],"categories":["Government of Australia","Commonwealth Government agencies of Australia","National archives","Film archives","Sound archives","Archives in Australia","Buildings and structures in Canberra","1984 establishments in Australia","Museums in Canberra","Cinema museums"],"headings":["History of the organisation","Collections","History of the building","Awards","Cochrane-Smith Award for Sound Heritage","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c6/National_Film_and_Sound_Archive.jpg/250px-National_Film_and_Sound_Archive.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/National_Film_and_Sound_Archive_viewed_near_McCoy_Circuit.jpg/220px